{"title_page": "Battle of La Marf\u00e9e", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| image        = Ch\u00e2teau de Beauregard - Louis, Count of Soissons.jpg\n|image_size    = 150px\n| caption      = French rebel leader Louis de Bourbon, Count of Soissons  \n| conflict     = Battle of La Marf\u00e9e\n| partof       = [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u201359)]]\n| date         = 6 July 1641\n| place        = [[La Marf\u00e9e]], near [[Sedan, France|Sedan]]\n| result       = Imperial-Spanish victory\n| combatant1   = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n| combatant2   = {{flagcountry|Holy Roman Empire}} <br/> {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Spanish Empire|Spain]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} French rebels\n| commander1   = {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Gaspard_III_de_Coligny|Ch\u00e2tillon]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} Marquis de Praslin {{KIA}} <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} Puys\u00e9gur <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} Marquis de Sourdis {{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n| commander2   = {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Guillaume_de_Lamboy,_Baron_of_Cortesheim|Guillaume de Lamboy]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Louis de Bourbon (1604-1641)|Comte de Soissons]] {{KIA}} <br/> {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon|duc de Bouillon]]\n| strength1      = 6,000 infantry, 1,400 cavalry {{sfn|Parrott|2003|p=214}}\n| strength2      = 7,000 infantry, 2,500 cavalry {{sfn|Parrott|2003|p=214}}\n| casualties1    = 200-300 killed or wounded <br/> 4,000 captured {{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n| casualties2    = Nominal\n}}\nThe '''Battle of La Marf\u00e9e''', also known as the '''Battle of Sedan''', took place on 6 July, 1641, during the 1635 to 1659 [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)|Franco-Spanish War]], a connected conflict of the [[Thirty Years War]]. \n\nIt was fought near [[Sedan, France]], on 6 July 1641, between a French army led by [[Gaspard_III_de_Coligny|Ch\u00e2tillon]], and an Imperial-Spanish army commanded by [[Guillaume_de_Lamboy,_Baron_of_Cortesheim|Guillaume de Lamboy]], supported by French rebels led by the [[Louis de Bourbon (1604-1641)|Comte de Soissons]] and Duke Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon, \n\nThe French army collapsed, but Soissons was killed in the closing moments, allegedly by using a loaded pistol to open his helmet, and the opportunity quickly passed.{{sfn|Elliott|1989|p=614}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:France 1552-1798.png|thumb|left|upright=1.25|France 1552-1798]]\n{{Campaignbox Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)}}\n{{Campaignbox Thirty Years' War}}\n17th century Europe was dominated by the struggle between the [[House_of_Bourbon|Bourbon]] kings of [[Kingdom_of_France|France]], and their [[House_of_Habsburg|Habsburg]] rivals in [[Habsburg_Spain|Spain]] and the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. Habsburg possessions bordered France in the [[Spanish Netherlands]], [[Franche-Comt\u00e9]], [[Alsace]], [[Roussillon]] and [[Duchy_of_Lorraine|Lorraine]] (see Map). France supported Habsburg opponents in the [[Thirty Years War]], the [[Eighty_Years'_War|Dutch Revolt]], and insurgencies in [[Portuguese_Restoration_War|Portugal]], [[Reapers' War|Catalonia]] and [[Kingdom_of_Naples|Naples]].{{sfn|Jensen|1985|pp=451-470}} \n\nFor their part, Spain and Austria financed Huguenot rebellions in South-Western France, and the [[C\u00e9vennes]], as well as internal conspiracies against the French government, led by [[Cardinal Richelieu]]. Although a major [[Battle_of_Castelnaudary|rebellion was defeated in 1632]], plotting continued, led by a mix of Huguenot exiles, and great feudal lords who resented their loss of power. Backed by Spanish money, some went to [[London]], seeking support from [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]; English foreign policy was generally pro-Spanish, but his wife was the [[Henrietta_Maria_of_France|younger sister of Louis XIII]], and the 1638 to 1651 [[War of the Three Kingdoms]] intervened.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=663}} \n\nFacing French-backed revolts in Catalonia and Portugal, in early 1641 Spanish chief minister [[Gaspar de Guzm\u00e1n, Count-Duke of Olivares|Olivares]] switched focus to the [[Louis de Bourbon, comte de Soissons|Comte de Soissons]] and [[Henry II, Duke of Guise|Henri II de Guise]]. Known as the 'Princes of Peace', since they claimed Richelieu was deliberately continuing the war to retain power, since 1637 they had been based in the [[Principality of Sedan]], then part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]].{{sfn|Elliott|1984|p=146}} This was held by the [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon|duc de Bouillon]]; like his younger brother, [[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Turenne]], Bouillon was brought up as a Protestant, and served with the Dutch army, before converting to Catholicism in 1634 and becoming a French general.{{sfn|Huberty, Giraud, Magdelaine|1985|pp=73,88}}\n\nThe French Army of Champagne occupied [[Duchy_of_Lorraine|Lorraine]] in 1634, then [[Breisach]] in 1638; by 1641, it was largely composed of low quality troops. All sides found it increasingly difficult to recruit and support armies on multiple fronts, so even a minor intervention could make a difference. Olivares planned simultaneous uprisings under Soissons in [[Principality of Sedan|Sedan]], with another in the south-western province of [[Guyenne]] that never materialised.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=664}} \n\nRichelieu was advised of the plot well in advance, and in April 1641, he ordered [[Gaspard_III_de_Coligny|Ch\u00e2tillon]] to invest Sedan; Ch\u00e2tillon objected, claiming to have less than 6,000 infantry and 1,400 cavalry, when he needed at least 8,000 infantry and 2,500 cavalry, plus a reserve force of 4,000 under Marquis de Sourdis.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=214}} In response to requests for support from Soissons, the [[Cardinal-Infante_Ferdinand_of_Austria|Governor of the Spanish Netherlands]] supplied him with money to recruit mercenaries, plus 7,000 men under [[Guillaume_de_Lamboy,_Baron_of_Cortesheim|Lamboy]].{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=148}} \n\n==The battle==\n{{Location map many|France Grand Est|caption = Eastern France, 1634 to 1644 (major battles indicated by dates)|relief=yes|border = black| width = 300| float = right\n|label =  Sedan|pos=left|lat_deg= 49|lat_min= 42|lon_deg = 4|lon_min = 26\n|label3 = Thionville(1639) |pos3= bottom|lat3_deg=49|lat3_min = 22|lon3_deg = 6|lon3_min = 10\n|label4 = Nancy(1634) |pos4= bottom|lat4_deg=48|lat4_min = 42|lon4_deg = 6|lon4_min = 11\n|label5 = Raucourt |pos5= left|lat5_deg=48|lat5_min = 56|lon5_deg = 6|lon5_min = 13\n|label6 = Rethel|pos6=left|lat6_deg=49|lat6_min =31 |lon6_deg = 4 |lon6_min = 22\n|label7=  Strasbourg|pos7= bottom|lat7_deg = 48|lat7_min = 35|lon7_deg = 7|lon7_min = 45\n|label8 = Rocroi(1643)|pos8 = right|lat8_deg = 49 | lat8_min = 56 | lon8_deg = 4 | lon8_min = 31\n|label9 = Breisach(1638)|pos9 = left|lat9_deg = 48 | lat9_min = 02 | lon9_deg = 7 | lon9_min = 35\n|label10 = Philipsburg|pos10 = left|lat10_deg = 49 | lat10_min = 14 | lon10_deg = 8 | lon10_min = 27\n|label11 = Reims|pos11 = bottom|lat11_deg = 49 |lat11_min = 16 |lon11_deg = 4|lon11_min = 02\n|label12 = La Marf\u00e9e(1641)|pos12 = right|lat12_deg = 49 |lat12_min = 42 | lon12_deg = 4 |lon12_min = 56\n}}\nOn 25 June, the French occupied positions opposite Sedan on the eastern bank of the [[Meuse]], but they were dislodged by cannon fire from the town. Ch\u00e2tillon moved further up the Meuse, to [[Remilly-Aillicourt]], with Lamboy's troops on the opposite bank at [[Bazeilles]]. Here he waited for promised reinforcements from [[Charles_IV,_Duke_of_Lorraine|Charles of Lorraine]], which never arrived.{{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=297}} \n\nSoissons and Bouillon left Sedan on 5 July with 3,000 French volunteers and [[Walloons|Walloon mercenaries]], taking position around the village of La Marf\u00e9e, where they were joined by Lamboy. The Spanish infantry deployed in a nearby wood under Lamboy, with Bouillon's cavalry on flat ground to their left, and Soissons with the reserve.{{sfn|Peyran|1826|pp=82\u201383}} \n\nThe morning of 6 July began with heavy rain, which delayed the French until after 10:00; they formed two columns, reaching La Marf\u00e9e an hour later. On arrival, Ch\u00e2tillon found his artillery, which consisted of four light guns, was in the rear, and so rather than waiting, sent his infantry into the woods.{{sfn|Puys\u00e9gur|1690|p=203}} \n\nThe Spanish initially gave ground, before the French ran into point blank artillery fire, and fell back. As they did so, Bouillon charged the French right; their commander, the Marquis de Praslin, was killed and his troops dissolved in panic, riding over their own infantry, who also broke. The cavalry on the left held their ground and retired in good order, but the battle was over in less than 45 minutes. The French lost 4,000 prisoners, plus their artillery and baggage train.{{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Frederic-Maurice de la Tour d'Auvergne, Duc de Bouillon LACMA AC1992.147.2.jpg|thumbnail|150px|left|[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon|duc de Bouillon]]]]\nCh\u00e2tillon, several of his senior officers, and 200 cavalry stopped at [[Rethel]], where they rallied the fugitives. Charles of Lorraine now joined Lamboy, who stopped to capture [[Donchery]], north of Sedan; this held them up until 14 July, allowing Ch\u00e2tillon and his remnants to reach [[Reims]]. Here they met [[Louis_XIII_of_France|Louis XIII]], and a small force under [[Urbain_de_Maill\u00e9-Br\u00e9z\u00e9|Maill\u00e9-Br\u00e9z\u00e9]].{{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n   \nSoissons died at the end of the action, apparently when a loaded pistol he was using to raise his helmet visor went off. Although his death ended the conspiracy, La Marf\u00e9e prevented Ch\u00e2tillon's army supporting the French offensive in [[Flanders]] as intended.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=148}} After [[Charles de La Porte|La Meilleraye]] captured [[Aire-sur-la-Lys]] on 27 July, Lamboy was sent north, where he joined the Cardinal-Infante; they re-captured [[Lillers]], then besieged Aire.{{sfn|Thion|2013|pp=27-28}} In an attempt to relieve the town, the French took [[Lens, Pas-de-Calais|Lens]], [[La Bass\u00e9e]] and [[Bapaume]], but Aire surrendered on 7 December.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=150}}    \n \nPlots against Richelieu continued until his death in December 1642, the most serious being that known as 'Cinq Mars' in June 1642. This featured many of those involved with Soissons, including [[Gaston, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Gaston of Orl\u00e9ans]], and the [[Henri Coiffier de Ruz\u00e9, Marquis of Cinq-Mars|Marquis de Cinq-Mars]], who was executed. Shortly before the French victory at [[Battle_of_Rocroi|Rocroi]] in May 1643, Louis XIII died, and was succeeded by his five year old son, [[Louis_XIV_of_France|Louis XIV]], a Regency Council ruling in his name. This resulted in a power struggle between the [[Anne_of_Austria|Queen Mother]], supported by [[Cardinal Mazarin]], and [[Louis II de Bourbon, Prince of Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]], victor of Rocroi, a member of the royal family, and effective ruler of large parts of eastern France.{{sfn|Monter|2007|p=118}}\n\nWhen Cond\u00e9 was arrested during the 1648 to 1653 [[Fronde]], Bouillon and Turenne joined forces to demand his release. Both switched sides in 1650, and in return for ceding Sedan and [[Raucourt]], Bouillon received the duchies of [[Duke of Albret|Albret]] and [[Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry]], plus the counties of [[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne]] and [[\u00c9vreux]]. He died at [[Pontoise]] on 9 August 1652.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises, 1621 to 1643 Volume III |date=1898 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=JH |title=The Count-Duke of Olivares: The Statesman in an Age of Decline |date=1989 |publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300044997 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=JH |title=Richelieu and Olivares (Cambridge Studies in Early Modern History) |date=1984 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521262057 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | author1=Huberty, Michel |author2=Giraud, Alain |author3=Magdelaine, F |title=L'Allemagne Dynastique, Tome IV -- Wittelsbach |year=1985 |publisher=Laballery |ref=harv| isbn=2-901138-04-7}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Monter |first1=William |title=Cultural Exchange in Early Modern Europe 1400-1700 (Volume 2)|date=1999 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521845472 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Parrott |first1=David |title=Richelieu's Army: War, Government and Society in France, 1624\u20131642|date=2001 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521792097|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Peyran |first1=Jacques |title=Histoire de l'ancienne principaut\u00e9 de Sedan, jusqu'\u00e0 la fin du dix-huiti\u00e8me si\u00e8cle, Volume II|date=1826 |publisher=Servier, Hennuy |location=Sedan |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Puys\u00e9gur |first1=Jacques de Chastenet |title=Les M\u00e9moires de Jacques de Chastenet, Seigneur de Puysegur Volume I |date=1690 |publisher=Abraham Wolfgang |location=Amsterdam |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Thion |first1=Stephane |title=French Armies of the Thirty Years War (Soldiers of the Past) |date=2013 |publisher=Histoire et Collections |isbn=978-2917747018 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Peter |title=Europe's Tragedy: A History of the Thirty Years War |date=2009 |publisher=Allen Lane |isbn=978-0713995923 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{coord|49.7025|N|4.9411|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Marfee, Battle Of}}\n[[Category:Battles of the Thirty Years' War]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1641 in France]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1641]]\n[[Category:Battles in Grand Est|La Marfee]]\n[[Category:History of Ardennes (department)|Battle of La Marfee]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)|La Marfee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| image        = Ch\u00e2teau de Beauregard - Louis, Count of Soissons.jpg\n|image_size    = 150px\n| caption      = French rebel leader Louis de Bourbon, Count of Soissons  \n| conflict     = Battle of La Marf\u00e9e\n| partof       = [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u201359)]]\n| date         = 6 July 1641\n| place        = [[La Marf\u00e9e]], near [[Sedan, France|Sedan]]\n| result       = Imperial-Spanish victory\n| combatant1   = {{flagcountry|Kingdom of France}}\n| combatant2   = {{flagcountry|Holy Roman Empire}} <br/> {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Spanish Empire|Spain]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} French rebels\n| commander1   = {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Gaspard_III_de_Coligny|Ch\u00e2tillon]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} Marquis de Praslin {{KIA}} <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} Puys\u00e9gur <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} Marquis de Sourdis {{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n| commander2   = {{flagicon|Spain|1506}} [[Guillaume_de_Lamboy,_Baron_of_Cortesheim|Guillaume de Lamboy]] <br/> {{flagicon|Kingdom of France}} [[Louis de Bourbon (1604-1641)|Comte de Soissons]] {{KIA}} <br/> {{flagicon|Holy Roman Empire}} [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon|duc de Bouillon]]\n| strength1      = 6,000 infantry, 1,400 cavalry {{sfn|Parrott|2003|p=214}}\n| strength2      = 7,000 infantry, 2,500 cavalry {{sfn|Parrott|2003|p=214}}\n| casualties1    = 200-300 killed or wounded <br/> 4,000 captured {{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n| casualties2    = Nominal\n}}\nThe '''Battle of La Marf\u00e9e''', also known as the '''Battle of Sedan''', took place on 6 July, 1641, during the 1635 to 1659 [[Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)|Franco-Spanish War]], a connected conflict of the [[Thirty Years War]]. \n\nIt was fought near [[Sedan, France]], on 6 July 1641, between a French army led by [[Gaspard_III_de_Coligny|Ch\u00e2tillon]], and an Imperial-Spanish army commanded by [[Guillaume_de_Lamboy,_Baron_of_Cortesheim|Guillaume de Lamboy]], supported by French rebels led by the [[Louis de Bourbon (1604-1641)|Comte de Soissons]] and Duke Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon, \n\nThe French army collapsed, but Soissons was killed in the closing moments, allegedly by using a loaded pistol to open his helmet, and the opportunity quickly passed.{{sfn|Elliott|1989|p=614}}\n\n==Background==\n[[File:France 1552-1798.png|thumb|left|upright=1.25|France 1552-1798]]\n{{Campaignbox Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)}}\n{{Campaignbox Thirty Years' War}}\n17th century Europe was dominated by the struggle between the [[House_of_Bourbon|Bourbon]] kings of [[Kingdom_of_France|France]], and their [[House_of_Habsburg|Habsburg]] rivals in [[Habsburg_Spain|Spain]] and the [[Holy Roman Empire]]. Habsburg possessions bordered France in the [[Spanish Netherlands]], [[Franche-Comt\u00e9]], [[Alsace]], [[Roussillon]] and [[Duchy_of_Lorraine|Lorraine]] (see Map). France supported Habsburg opponents in the [[Thirty Years War]], the [[Eighty_Years'_War|Dutch Revolt]], and insurgencies in [[Portuguese_Restoration_War|Portugal]], [[Reapers' War|Catalonia]] and [[Kingdom_of_Naples|Naples]].{{sfn|Jensen|1985|pp=451-470}} \n\nFor their part, Spain and Austria financed Huguenot rebellions in South-Western France, and the [[C\u00e9vennes]], as well as internal conspiracies against the French government, led by [[Cardinal Richelieu]]. Although a major [[Battle_of_Castelnaudary|rebellion was defeated in 1632]], plotting continued, led by a mix of Huguenot exiles, and great feudal lords who resented their loss of power. Backed by Spanish money, some went to [[London]], seeking support from [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]; English foreign policy was generally pro-Spanish, but his wife was the [[Henrietta_Maria_of_France|younger sister of Louis XIII]], and the 1638 to 1651 [[War of the Three Kingdoms]] intervened.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=663}} \n\nFacing French-backed revolts in Catalonia and Portugal, in early 1641 Spanish chief minister [[Gaspar de Guzm\u00e1n, Count-Duke of Olivares|Olivares]] switched focus to the [[Louis de Bourbon, comte de Soissons|Comte de Soissons]] and [[Henry II, Duke of Guise|Henri II de Guise]]. Known as the 'Princes of Peace', since they claimed Richelieu was deliberately continuing the war to retain power, since 1637 they had been based in the [[Principality of Sedan]], then part of the [[Holy Roman Empire]].{{sfn|Elliott|1984|p=146}} This was held by the [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon|duc de Bouillon]]; like his younger brother, [[Henri_de_La_Tour_d'Auvergne,_Viscount_of_Turenne|Turenne]], Bouillon was brought up as a Protestant, and served with the Dutch army, before converting to Catholicism in 1634 and becoming a French general.{{sfn|Huberty, Giraud, Magdelaine|1985|pp=73,88}}\n\nThe French Army of Champagne occupied [[Duchy_of_Lorraine|Lorraine]] in 1634, then [[Breisach]] in 1638; by 1641, it was largely composed of low quality troops. All sides found it increasingly difficult to recruit and support armies on multiple fronts, so even a minor intervention could make a difference. Olivares planned simultaneous uprisings under Soissons in [[Sedan]], with another in the south-western province of [[Guyenne]] that never materialised.{{sfn|Wilson|2009|p=664}} \n\nRichelieu was advised of the plot well in advance, and in April 1641, he ordered [[Gaspard_III_de_Coligny|Ch\u00e2tillon]] to invest Sedan; Ch\u00e2tillon objected, claiming to have less than 6,000 infantry and 1,400 cavalry, when he needed at least 8,000 infantry and 2,500 cavalry, plus a reserve force of 4,000 under Marquis de Sourdis.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=214}} In response to requests for support from Soissons, the [[Cardinal-Infante_Ferdinand_of_Austria|Governor of the Spanish Netherlands]] supplied him with money to recruit mercenaries, plus 7,000 men under [[Guillaume_de_Lamboy,_Baron_of_Cortesheim|Lamboy]].{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=148}} \n\n==The battle==\n{{Location map many|France Grand Est|caption = Eastern France, 1634 to 1644 (major battles indicated by dates)|relief=yes|border = black| width = 300| float = right\n|label =  Sedan|pos=left|lat_deg= 49|lat_min= 42|lon_deg = 4|lon_min = 26\n|label3 = Thionville(1639) |pos3= bottom|lat3_deg=49|lat3_min = 22|lon3_deg = 6|lon3_min = 10\n|label4 = Nancy(1634) |pos4= bottom|lat4_deg=48|lat4_min = 42|lon4_deg = 6|lon4_min = 11\n|label5 = Raucourt |pos5= left|lat5_deg=48|lat5_min = 56|lon5_deg = 6|lon5_min = 13\n|label6 = Rethel|pos6=left|lat6_deg=49|lat6_min =31 |lon6_deg = 4 |lon6_min = 22\n|label7=  Strasbourg|pos7= bottom|lat7_deg = 48|lat7_min = 35|lon7_deg = 7|lon7_min = 45\n|label8 = Rocroi(1643)|pos8 = right|lat8_deg = 49 | lat8_min = 56 | lon8_deg = 4 | lon8_min = 31\n|label9 = Breisach(1638)|pos9 = left|lat9_deg = 48 | lat9_min = 02 | lon9_deg = 7 | lon9_min = 35\n|label10 = Philipsburg|pos10 = left|lat10_deg = 49 | lat10_min = 14 | lon10_deg = 8 | lon10_min = 27\n|label11 = Reims|pos11 = bottom|lat11_deg = 49 |lat11_min = 16 |lon11_deg = 4|lon11_min = 02\n|label12 = La Marf\u00e9e(1641)|pos12 = right|lat12_deg = 49 |lat12_min = 42 | lon12_deg = 4 |lon12_min = 56\n}}\nOn 25 June, the French occupied positions opposite Sedan on the eastern bank of the [[Meuse]], but they were dislodged by cannon fire from the town. Ch\u00e2tillon moved further up the Meuse, to [[Remilly-Aillicourt]], with Lamboy's troops on the opposite bank at [[Bazeilles]]. Here he waited for promised reinforcements from [[Charles_IV,_Duke_of_Lorraine|Charles of Lorraine]], which never arrived.{{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=297}} \n\nSoissons and Bouillon left Sedan on 5 July with 3,000 French volunteers and [[Walloons|Walloon mercenaries]], taking position around the village of La Marf\u00e9e, where they were joined by Lamboy. The Spanish infantry deployed in a nearby wood under Lamboy, with Bouillon's cavalry on flat ground to their left, and Soissons with the reserve.{{sfn|Peyran|1826|pp=82\u201383}} \n\nThe morning of 6 July began with heavy rain, which delayed the French until after 10:00; they formed two columns, reaching La Marf\u00e9e an hour later. On arrival, Ch\u00e2tillon found his artillery, which consisted of four light guns, was in the rear, and so rather than waiting, sent his infantry into the woods.{{sfn|Puys\u00e9gur|1690|p=203}} \n\nThe Spanish initially gave ground, before the French ran into point blank artillery fire, and fell back. As they did so, Bouillon charged the French right; their commander, the Marquis de Praslin, was killed and his troops dissolved in panic, riding over their own infantry, who also broke. The cavalry on the left held their ground and retired in good order, but the battle was over in less than 45 minutes. The French lost 4,000 prisoners, plus their artillery and baggage train.{{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n\n==Aftermath==\n[[File:Frederic-Maurice de la Tour d'Auvergne, Duc de Bouillon LACMA AC1992.147.2.jpg|thumbnail|150px|left|[[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Maurice de La Tour d'Auvergne, duc de Bouillon|duc de Bouillon]]]]\nCh\u00e2tillon, several of his senior officers, and 200 cavalry stopped at [[Rethel]], where they rallied the fugitives. Charles of Lorraine now joined Lamboy, who stopped to capture [[Donchery]], north of Sedan; this held them up until 14 July, allowing Ch\u00e2tillon and his remnants to reach [[Reims]]. Here they met [[Louis_XIII_of_France|Louis XIII]], and a small force under [[Urbain_de_Maill\u00e9-Br\u00e9z\u00e9|Maill\u00e9-Br\u00e9z\u00e9]].{{sfn|De P\u00e9rini|1898|p=300}}\n   \nSoissons died at the end of the action, apparently when a loaded pistol he was using to raise his helmet visor went off. Although his death ended the conspiracy, La Marf\u00e9e prevented Ch\u00e2tillon's army supporting the French offensive in [[Flanders]] as intended.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=148}} After [[Charles de La Porte|La Meilleraye]] captured [[Aire-sur-la-Lys]] on 27 July, Lamboy was sent north, where he joined the Cardinal-Infante; they re-captured [[Lillers]], then besieged Aire.{{sfn|Thion|2013|pp=27-28}} In an attempt to relieve the town, the French took [[Lens, Pas-de-Calais|Lens]], [[La Bass\u00e9e]] and [[Bapaume]], but Aire surrendered on 7 December.{{sfn|Parrott|2001|p=150}}    \n \nPlots against Richelieu continued until his death in December 1642, the most serious being that known as 'Cinq Mars' in June 1642. This featured many of those involved with Soissons, including [[Gaston, Duke of Orl\u00e9ans|Gaston of Orl\u00e9ans]], and the [[Henri Coiffier de Ruz\u00e9, Marquis of Cinq-Mars|Marquis de Cinq-Mars]], who was executed. Shortly before the French victory at [[Battle_of_Rocroi|Rocroi]] in May 1643, Louis XIII died, and was succeeded by his five year old son, [[Louis_XIV_of_France|Louis XIV]], a Regency Council ruling in his name. This resulted in a power struggle between the [[Anne_of_Austria|Queen Mother]], supported by [[Cardinal Mazarin]], and [[Louis II de Bourbon, Prince of Cond\u00e9|Cond\u00e9]], victor of Rocroi, a member of the royal family, and effective ruler of large parts of eastern France.{{sfn|Monter|2007|p=118}}\n\nWhen Cond\u00e9 was arrested during the 1648 to 1653 [[Fronde]], Bouillon and Turenne joined forces to demand his release. Both switched sides in 1650, and in return for ceding Sedan and [[Raucourt]], Bouillon received the duchies of [[Duke of Albret|Albret]] and [[Ch\u00e2teau-Thierry]], plus the counties of [[Auvergne (province)|Auvergne]] and [[\u00c9vreux]]. He died at [[Pontoise]] on 9 August 1652.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{cite book |last1=De P\u00e9rini |first1=Hard\u00ff |title=Batailles fran\u00e7aises, 1621 to 1643 Volume III |date=1898 |publisher=Ernest Flammarion, Paris|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=JH |title=The Count-Duke of Olivares: The Statesman in an Age of Decline |date=1989 |publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0300044997 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=JH |title=Richelieu and Olivares (Cambridge Studies in Early Modern History) |date=1984 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521262057 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | author1=Huberty, Michel |author2=Giraud, Alain |author3=Magdelaine, F |title=L'Allemagne Dynastique, Tome IV -- Wittelsbach |year=1985 |publisher=Laballery |ref=harv| isbn=2-901138-04-7}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Monter |first1=William |title=Cultural Exchange in Early Modern Europe 1400-1700 (Volume 2)|date=1999 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521845472 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Parrott |first1=David |title=Richelieu's Army: War, Government and Society in France, 1624\u20131642|date=2001 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0521792097|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Peyran |first1=Jacques |title=Histoire de l'ancienne principaut\u00e9 de Sedan, jusqu'\u00e0 la fin du dix-huiti\u00e8me si\u00e8cle, Volume II|date=1826 |publisher=Servier, Hennuy |location=Sedan |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Puys\u00e9gur |first1=Jacques de Chastenet |title=Les M\u00e9moires de Jacques de Chastenet, Seigneur de Puysegur Volume I |date=1690 |publisher=Abraham Wolfgang |location=Amsterdam |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Thion |first1=Stephane |title=French Armies of the Thirty Years War (Soldiers of the Past) |date=2013 |publisher=Histoire et Collections |isbn=978-2917747018 |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last1=Wilson |first1=Peter |title=Europe's Tragedy: A History of the Thirty Years War |date=2009 |publisher=Allen Lane |isbn=978-0713995923 |ref=harv}}\n\n{{coord|49.7025|N|4.9411|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:La Marfee, Battle Of}}\n[[Category:Battles of the Thirty Years' War]]\n[[Category:Battles involving France]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Holy Roman Empire]]\n[[Category:1641 in France]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1641]]\n[[Category:Battles in Grand Est|La Marfee]]\n[[Category:History of Ardennes (department)|Battle of La Marfee]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Franco-Spanish War (1635\u20131659)|La Marfee]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toSedan(link changed toPrincipality of Sedan) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_La_Marf%C3%A9e"}
{"title_page": "Vadodara", "text_new": "{{original research|date=February 2020}}\n\n{{About|the municipality in India|its namesake district|Vadodara district|the constituency|Vadodara (Lok Sabha constituency)}}\n{{redirect|Baroda}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Vadodara\n| other_name                      = Baroda\n| official_name                   = Vadodara\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any India script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = [[Metropolis]]\n| image_skyline                   = \n{{Photomontage\n| photo1a =Laxmi Vilas Palace, Vadodara.jpg\n| photo2a =NyayM.jpg\n| photo2b =Sardar Patel Planetarium Vadodara.jpg\n| photo3a =Baroda Techo.jpg\n| size                            = 280\n| spacing                         = 1\n| position                        = centre\n| border                          = 0\n| color                           = white \n}}\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from top: [[Lakshmi Vilas Palace]], Saradar Patel Planetarium, [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]], [[Nyay Mandir]] in the heart of Vadodara,    \n| nickname                        = Sayaji Nagari (City of Sayajirao Gaekwad), Sanskari Nagari (Cultural City)\n| map_caption                     = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Gujarat\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location of Vadodara in [[Gujarat]]\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|22|18|N|73|12|E|region:IN-GJ|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flagicon|IND}} [[India]]\n| subdivision_type1               = State\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Gujarat]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Vadodara District]]\n| subdivision_type3               = Zone\n| subdivision_name3               = 4<ref name=\"zone\"/>\n| subdivision_type4               = Ward\n| subdivision_name4               = 25<ref name=\"zone\"/><ref name=\"Ward\">{{cite web |publisher=Vadodara Municipal Corporation |title=Ward Office Details |url=https://vmc.gov.in/WardDetails.aspx |accessdate=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002070657/https://vmc.gov.in/WardDetails.aspx |archive-date=2 October 2017 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n| established_title               = [[Vadodara Municipal Corporation]]\n| established_date                = Established 1950\n| governing_body                  = [[Vadodara Urban Development Authority|VUDA]], [[Vadodara Mahanagar Seva Sadan|VMSS]]\n| leader_title1                   = [[Mayor]]\n| leader_name1                    = Jigeesha Sheth\n| leader_title2                   = [[Municipal Commissioner (India)|Municipal Commissioner]]\n| leader_name2                    = Nalin Upadhyay\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref name=\"zone\"/>\n| area_total_km2                  = 410\n| area_rank                       = 18\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 32\n| population_footnotes            = <ref name=\"WG\">[http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf Cities having population 1 lakh and above, Census 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723151530/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf |date=23 July 2013 }}. censusindia.gov.in</ref>\n| population_total                = 1,822,221 <ref name=\"WG\">[http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf Cities having population 1 lakh and above, Census 2011] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723151530/http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf |date=23 July 2013 }}. censusindia.gov.in</ref>\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_rank                 = 20th (3rd in Gujarat State)\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = Vadodarian, Barodian\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 390 0XX\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| area_code                       = (91)265\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN]]\n| registration_plate              = GJ-06 (Urban)/GJ-29 (Rural)\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Village\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Ahmedabad, Gujarat|Ahmedabad]]\n| blank2_name_sec1                = Nearest city\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Bharuch, Gujarat|Bharuch]], [[Anand, Gujarat|Anand]]\n| blank3_name_sec1                = [[Literacy Rate]]\n| blank3_info_sec1                = 94.5%\n| blank4_name_sec1                = Legislature type\n| blank4_info_sec1                = [[Municipal Corporation]]\n| blank5_name_sec1                = Legislature Strength\n| blank5_info_sec1                = 84<ref name=\"zone\"/>\n| blank6_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank6_info_sec1                = 1<ref name=\"LSMLA\"/>\n| blank7_name_sec1                = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank7_info_sec1                = 13<ref name=\"MLA\"/>\n| blank1_name_sec2                = [[Climate of India|Climate]]\n| blank1_info_sec2                = [[Climatic regions of India#Tropical wet and dry or savanna climate|Tropical savanna]] {{small|([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: Aw)}}\n| blank2_name_sec2                = [[Urban planning|Planning]] agency\n| blank2_info_sec2                = 1 ([[Vadodara Urban Development Authority|VUDA]])\n| blank3_name_sec2                = Distance from Gandhinagar\n| blank3_info_sec2                = {{convert|126|km|mi}} NE (Rail & Air)\n| blank4_name_sec2                = Distance from Mumbai\n| blank4_info_sec2                = {{convert|395|km|mi}} S (Rail & Air)\n| blank5_name_sec2                = Distance from Ahmedabad\n| blank5_info_sec2                = {{convert|100|km|mi}} NW (Road)\n| website                         = {{URL|www.vmc.gov.in}}\n}}\n'''Vadodara''' ({{IPA-gu|\u028b\u0259\u02c8\u027dod\u0259\u027e\u0251\u02d0}}; formerly known as '''Baroda''') is a large<ref name=name>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/3455/8/08_chapter%204.pdf CHAPTER \u2013 4 PROFILE OF SELECTED CITIES OF GUJARAT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022194829/http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/3455/8/08_chapter%204.pdf |date=22 October 2012 }}. inflibnet.ac.in</ref> city in the [[India]]n state of [[Gujarat]].  It is the administrative headquarters of [[Vadodara District]] and is located on the banks of the [[Vishwamitri]] river (originating from Pavagadh), {{convert|141|km}} from the state capital [[Gandhinagar]]. The railway line and [[National Highway 8 (India)(old numbering)|NH 8]] that connect [[Delhi]] and [[Mumbai]] pass through Vadodara. It is known as a Sanskari Nagari (city)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baroda.com/aboutvadodara.php|title=About Vadodara|website=www.baroda.com|access-date=2019-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411052514/http://www.baroda.com/aboutvadodara.php|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> of India.\n\nThe city is known for the [[Lakshmi Vilas Palace]], the residence of [[Baroda State]]'s [[Maratha]] royal family, the [[Gaekwad]]s, of the Gaekwad Dynasty. It is also the home of the [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\nThe '''city''' used to be called Chandanavati after its ruler Raja Chandan of the Dodiya of [[Rajput]]s. The capital was also known as Virakshetra or Viravati (Land of Warriors). Later on, it was known as Vadpatraka or Vadodar\u00e1, which according to tradition is a corrupt form of the [[Sanskrit]] word ''vatodar'' meaning in the belly of the Banyan tree. It is now almost impossible to ascertain when the various changes in the name were made; but early English travellers and merchants mention the town as Brodera,<ref name=painting>{{cite web|publisher=Collect Britain, British Library|title=Hand Painting of Bridge over the River Vishwamitri, near Brodera|url=http://www.collectbritain.com/personalisation/object.cfm?uid=019XZZ0000455C9U00087000&largeimage=1#largeimage|accessdate=3 July 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928134532/http://www.collectbritain.com/personalisation/object.cfm?uid=019XZZ0000455C9U00087000&largeimage=1#largeimage|archive-date=28 September 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and it is from this that the name Baroda is derived. In 1974, the official name of the city was changed to Vadodara.\n\nIn 1907, a small [[Baroda, Michigan|village]] and [[Baroda Township, Michigan|township]]<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |publisher=Berrien County Community Development Department, Michigan |title=Village of Baroda|url=http://www.berriencounty.org/econdev/pdfs/Baroda%20Village.pdf?PHPSESSID=6ab1c85699c1bc3938fd03e51eb704ac |accessdate=27 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927161115/http://www.berriencounty.org/econdev/pdfs/Baroda%20Village.pdf?PHPSESSID=6ab1c85699c1bc3938fd03e51eb704ac <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref> in [[Michigan]], United States, were named after Baroda.\n\n===Old Ankotakka===\nIt is believed that early man lived on the banks of the [[Mahi River]], which formed the floodplain during that age.<ref>{{cite web|title = History of Vadodara \u2013 Baroda|url = http://www.historyofvadodara.in/introduction/|website = Introduction {{!}} History of Vadodara \u2013 Baroda|accessdate = 17 March 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160102204629/http://www.historyofvadodara.in/introduction/|archive-date = 2 January 2016|url-status = live|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The movements of these [[hunter-gatherers]], living on the banks of the river, grubbing the roots and killing animals with crude stone tools made out of the cobbles and pebbles available on the river bank, were necessarily controlled by the availability of convenient raw materials for their tools.\n\n===Recent history===\n{{main|Baroda State}}\n\n[[Baroda State]] was a former Indian State. Vadodara's more recent history began when the [[Maratha]] general [[Pilaji Gaekwad]] conquered [[Songadh]] from the Mughals in 1726.<ref name=Gaekwad>{{cite web |publisher=The Royal Ark |title=Baroda State History |url=http://www.4dw.net/royalark/India/baroda.htm |accessdate=14 June 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402171209/http://www.4dw.net/royalark/India/baroda.htm |archive-date=2 April 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Before the Gaekwads captured Baroda, it was ruled by the [[Babi (title)|Babi]] [[Nawab]]s, who were the officers of the Mughal rulers. Most notably, from 1705\u20131716, Sardar [[Senapati]] Khanderao Dabhade led the Maratha Empire forces in Baroda. Except for a short period, Baroda continued to be in the reign of the Gaekwads from 1734 to 1948. Initially detailed to collect revenue on behalf of the [[Peshwa]] in Gujarat, [[Pilaji Gaekwad]] remained there to carve out a kingdom for himself. Damajirao, who was son and successor of Pilaji Gaekwad, defeated the Mughal armies and conquered Baroda in 1734.<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/> His successors consolidated their power over large tracts of Gujarat, becoming easily the most powerful rulers in the region.\n\nAfter the Maratha defeat in the [[Third Battle of Panipat]] in 1761,<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/> control of the empire by the Peshwas weakened as it became a loose [[Confederation|confederacy]], and the Gaekwad [[Maharaja]]s ruled the kingdom until it [[Instrument of Accession|acceded]] to Independent [[Republic of India]] in 1949. In 1802,<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/> the British intervened to defend a [[Maharaja]] that had recently inherited the throne from rival claimants, and Vadodara concluded a [[subsidiary alliance]] with the British that recognised the Kingdom as a [[Princely state]] and allowed the Maharajas of Baroda internal political sovereignty in return for recognising British 'Paramountcy', a form of [[suzerainty]] in which the control of the state's foreign affairs was completely surrendered. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nThe golden period in the Maratha rule of Vadodara started with the accession of [[Maharaja Sayajirao Gaekwad III|Maharaja Sayajirao III]] in 1875.<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nVadodara is located at {{coord|22.30|N|73.19|E|}} in western India at an elevation of {{convert|39|m}}. It is the 18th-largest city in India with an area of {{convert|235|km2}} and a population of 2.1 million, according to the 2010\u201311 census. The city sits on the banks of the [[Vishwamitri River]], in central Gujarat. The Vishwamitri frequently dries up in the summer, leaving only a small stream of [[water]]. The city is located on the fertile plain between the [[Mahi River|Mahi]] and [[Narmada River]]s. According to the Bureau of Indian Standards, the cosmopolis falls under [[Earthquake hazard zoning of India|seismic zone-III]], in a scale of I to V (in order of increasing proneness to earthquakes).<ref name=hazardprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsdma.org/hazard/eq/200_year.jpg |title=Gujarat Earthquake Hazard Risk Zone |accessdate=23 August 2006 |publisher=Gujarat State Disaster Management Authority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929061637/http://www.gsdma.org/hazard/eq/200_year.jpg |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n{{wide image|Baroda Lvp.JPG|1000x300px|align-cap=center|Panorama of Laxmi Vilas Palace}}\n\n==Climate==\n\nDespite the roughly 800&nbsp;mm of precipitation that the city receives annually, Vadodara features a [[semi-arid climate]] (BSh) under [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen's Climate classification]] due to the area's high [[potential evapotranspiration]]. There are three main seasons: Summer, [[Monsoon]] and Winter. Aside from the monsoon season, the climate is dry. The weather is hot during March to July, when the average maximum is {{convert|45|\u00b0C}}, and the average minimum is {{convert|23|C}}. From November to February, the average maximum temperature is {{convert|30|\u00b0C}}, the average minimum is {{convert|15|\u00b0C}}, and the climate is extremely dry. Cold northerly winds are responsible for a mild chilly days in January. The southwest monsoon brings a humid climate from mid-June to mid-September. The average rainfall is {{convert|93|cm|in|abbr=on}}, but infrequent heavy torrential rains cause the river to flood<ref name=\"Weatherbase\">{{cite web|title=Baroda, India (2~35 kilometers)|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=74724&units=metric|accessdate=6 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211144022/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=74724&units=metric|archive-date=11 December 2013|url-status=live}}{{better source|date=December 2013}}</ref> like the [[2005 Gujarat Flood|2005 Gujarat flood]] or the [[2008 Indian floods]] which were catastrophic.<ref name=\"floods\">{{cite web | url=http://www.iahv.org/in-en/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Gujarat-Floods-2005-Report.pdf | title=Gujarat Floods 2005: Project Report | publisher=International Association for Human Values and the Art of Living | date=2005 | accessdate=2 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112001510/http://www.iahv.org/in-en/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Gujarat-Floods-2005-Report.pdf | archive-date=12 January 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe highest recorded temperature was {{convert|46.7|C}} on 11 May 1960 crossed with {{convert|48.0|C}} on 19 May 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accuweather.com/en/in/vadodara/202439/may-weather/202439|title=Vadodara May Weather 2016 \u2013 AccuWeather Forecast for Gujarat India|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930070904/http://www.accuweather.com/en/in/vadodara/202439/may-weather/202439|archive-date=30 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while the lowest recorded temperature was {{convert|-1.1|C}} on 15 January 1935.<ref name=\"IMD\">{{cite web |url=http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf |title=Ever Recorded Maximum/Minimum Temperature up to 2010 |publisher=India Meteorological Department |accessdate=16 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316064314/http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf |archive-date=16 March 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n{{weather box|width=auto\n|location = Vadodara\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 36.2\n|Feb record high C = 41.7\n|Mar record high C = 44.4\n|Apr record high C = 45.9\n|May record high C = 48.0\n|Jun record high C = 45.6\n|Jul record high C = 40.6\n|Aug record high C = 37.9\n|Sep record high C = 41.1\n|Oct record high C = 42.1\n|Nov record high C = 39.6\n|Dec record high C = 36.8\n\n|Jan high C = 29.5\n|Feb high C = 31.9\n|Mar high C = 36.2\n|Apr high C = 39.2\n|May high C = 40.1\n|Jun high C = 36.8\n|Jul high C = 32.5\n|Aug high C = 31.4\n|Sep high C = 33.0\n|Oct high C = 35.5\n|Nov high C = 33.4\n|Dec high C = 30.7\n\n|Jan low C = 12.5\n|Feb low C = 14.2\n|Mar low C = 18.4\n|Apr low C = 23.0\n|May low C = 26.6\n|Jun low C = 27.0\n|Jul low C = 25.8\n|Aug low C = 25.0\n|Sep low C = 24.5\n|Oct low C = 21.4\n|Nov low C = 16.9\n|Dec low C = 13.7\n\n|Jan record low C = \u22121.1\n|Feb record low C =  1.7\n|Mar record low C =  6.7\n|Apr record low C = 11.7\n|May record low C = 18.9\n|Jun r