            = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 390 0XX\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| area_code                       = (91)265\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN]]\n| registration_plate              = GJ-06 (Urban)/GJ-29 (Rural)\n| blank1_name_sec1                = Village\n| blank1_info_sec1                = [[Ahmedabad, Gujarat|Ahmedabad]]\n| blank2_name_sec1                = Nearest city\n| blank2_info_sec1                = [[Bharuch, Gujarat|Bharuch]], [[Anand, Gujarat|Anand]]\n| blank3_name_sec1                = [[Literacy Rate]]\n| blank3_info_sec1                = 94.5%\n| blank4_name_sec1                = Legislature type\n| blank4_info_sec1                = [[Municipal Corporation]]\n| blank5_name_sec1                = Legislature Strength\n| blank5_info_sec1                = 84<ref name=\"zone\"/>\n| blank6_name_sec1                = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank6_info_sec1                = 1<ref name=\"LSMLA\"/>\n| blank7_name_sec1                = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank7_info_sec1                = 13<ref name=\"MLA\"/>\n| blank1_name_sec2                = [[Climate of India|Climate]]\n| blank1_info_sec2                = [[Climatic regions of India#Tropical wet and dry or savanna climate|Tropical savanna]] {{small|([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]]: Aw)}}\n| blank2_name_sec2                = [[Urban planning|Planning]] agency\n| blank2_info_sec2                = 1 ([[Vadodara Urban Development Authority|VUDA]])\n| blank3_name_sec2                = Distance from Gandhinagar\n| blank3_info_sec2                = {{convert|126|km|mi}} NE (Rail & Air)\n| blank4_name_sec2                = Distance from Mumbai\n| blank4_info_sec2                = {{convert|395|km|mi}} S (Rail & Air)\n| blank5_name_sec2                = Distance from Ahmedabad\n| blank5_info_sec2                = {{convert|100|km|mi}} NW (Road)\n| website                         = {{URL|www.vmc.gov.in}}\n}}\n'''Vadodara''' ({{IPA-gu|\u028b\u0259\u02c8\u027dod\u0259\u027e\u0251\u02d0}}; formerly known as '''Baroda''') is a large<ref name=name>[http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/3455/8/08_chapter%204.pdf CHAPTER \u2013 4 PROFILE OF SELECTED CITIES OF GUJARAT] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022194829/http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/3455/8/08_chapter%204.pdf |date=22 October 2012 }}. inflibnet.ac.in</ref> city in the [[India]]n state of [[Gujarat]].  It is the administrative headquarters of [[Vadodara District]] and is located on the banks of the [[Vishwamitri]] river, {{convert|141|km}} from the state capital [[Gandhinagar]]. The railway line and [[National Highway 8 (India)(old numbering)|NH 8]] that connect [[Delhi]] and [[Mumbai]] pass through Vadodara. It is known as a Sanskari Nagari (city)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.baroda.com/aboutvadodara.php|title=About Vadodara|website=www.baroda.com|access-date=2019-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411052514/http://www.baroda.com/aboutvadodara.php|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> of India.\n\nThe city is known for the [[Lakshmi Vilas Palace]], the residence of [[Baroda State]]'s [[Maratha]] royal family, the [[Gaekwad]]s, of the Gaekwad Dynasty. It is also the home of the [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\nThe '''city''' used to be called Chandanavati after its ruler Raja Chandan of the Dodiya of [[Rajput]]s. The capital was also known as Virakshetra or Viravati (Land of Warriors). Later on, it was known as Vadpatraka or Vadodar\u00e1, which according to tradition is a corrupt form of the [[Sanskrit]] word ''vatodar'' meaning in the belly of the Banyan tree. It is now almost impossible to ascertain when the various changes in the name were made; but early English travellers and merchants mention the town as Brodera,<ref name=painting>{{cite web|publisher=Collect Britain, British Library|title=Hand Painting of Bridge over the River Vishwamitri, near Brodera|url=http://www.collectbritain.com/personalisation/object.cfm?uid=019XZZ0000455C9U00087000&largeimage=1#largeimage|accessdate=3 July 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928134532/http://www.collectbritain.com/personalisation/object.cfm?uid=019XZZ0000455C9U00087000&largeimage=1#largeimage|archive-date=28 September 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> and it is from this that the name Baroda is derived. In 1974, the official name of the city was changed to Vadodara.\n\nIn 1907, a small [[Baroda, Michigan|village]] and [[Baroda Township, Michigan|township]]<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |publisher=Berrien County Community Development Department, Michigan |title=Village of Baroda|url=http://www.berriencounty.org/econdev/pdfs/Baroda%20Village.pdf?PHPSESSID=6ab1c85699c1bc3938fd03e51eb704ac |accessdate=27 June 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927161115/http://www.berriencounty.org/econdev/pdfs/Baroda%20Village.pdf?PHPSESSID=6ab1c85699c1bc3938fd03e51eb704ac <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 27 September 2007}}</ref> in [[Michigan]], United States, were named after Baroda.\n\n===Old Ankotakka===\nIt is believed that early man lived on the banks of the [[Mahi River]], which formed the floodplain during that age.<ref>{{cite web|title = History of Vadodara \u2013 Baroda|url = http://www.historyofvadodara.in/introduction/|website = Introduction {{!}} History of Vadodara \u2013 Baroda|accessdate = 17 March 2015|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160102204629/http://www.historyofvadodara.in/introduction/|archive-date = 2 January 2016|url-status = live|df = dmy-all}}</ref> The movements of these [[hunter-gatherers]], living on the banks of the river, grubbing the roots and killing animals with crude stone tools made out of the cobbles and pebbles available on the river bank, were necessarily controlled by the availability of convenient raw materials for their tools.\n\n===Recent history===\n{{main|Baroda State}}\n\n[[Baroda State]] was a former Indian State. Vadodara's more recent history began when the [[Maratha]] general [[Pilaji Gaekwad]] conquered [[Songadh]] from the Mughals in 1726.<ref name=Gaekwad>{{cite web |publisher=The Royal Ark |title=Baroda State History |url=http://www.4dw.net/royalark/India/baroda.htm |accessdate=14 June 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070402171209/http://www.4dw.net/royalark/India/baroda.htm |archive-date=2 April 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref> Before the Gaekwads captured Baroda, it was ruled by the [[Babi (title)|Babi]] [[Nawab]]s, who were the officers of the Mughal rulers. Most notably, from 1705\u20131716, Sardar [[Senapati]] Khanderao Dabhade led the Maratha Empire forces in Baroda. Except for a short period, Baroda continued to be in the reign of the Gaekwads from 1734 to 1948. Initially detailed to collect revenue on behalf of the [[Peshwa]] in Gujarat, [[Pilaji Gaekwad]] remained there to carve out a kingdom for himself. Damajirao, who was son and successor of Pilaji Gaekwad, defeated the Mughal armies and conquered Baroda in 1734.<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/> His successors consolidated their power over large tracts of Gujarat, becoming easily the most powerful rulers in the region.\n\nAfter the Maratha defeat in the [[Third Battle of Panipat]] in 1761,<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/> control of the empire by the Peshwas weakened as it became a loose [[Confederation|confederacy]], and the Gaekwad [[Maharaja]]s ruled the kingdom until it [[Instrument of Accession|acceded]] to Independent [[Republic of India]] in 1949. In 1802,<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/> the British intervened to defend a [[Maharaja]] that had recently inherited the throne from rival claimants, and Vadodara concluded a [[subsidiary alliance]] with the British that recognised the Kingdom as a [[Princely state]] and allowed the Maharajas of Baroda internal political sovereignty in return for recognising British 'Paramountcy', a form of [[suzerainty]] in which the control of the state's foreign affairs was completely surrendered. {{citation needed|date=January 2015}}\n\nThe golden period in the Maratha rule of Vadodara started with the accession of [[Maharaja Sayajirao Gaekwad III|Maharaja Sayajirao III]] in 1875.<ref name=\"Gaekwad\"/>\n\n==Geography==\nVadodara is located at {{coord|22.30|N|73.19|E|}} in western India at an elevation of {{convert|39|m}}. It is the 18th-largest city in India with an area of {{convert|235|km2}} and a population of 2.1 million, according to the 2010\u201311 census. The city sits on the banks of the [[Vishwamitri River]], in central Gujarat. The Vishwamitri frequently dries up in the summer, leaving only a small stream of [[water]]. The city is located on the fertile plain between the [[Mahi River|Mahi]] and [[Narmada River]]s. According to the Bureau of Indian Standards, the cosmopolis falls under [[Earthquake hazard zoning of India|seismic zone-III]], in a scale of I to V (in order of increasing proneness to earthquakes).<ref name=hazardprofile>{{cite web|url=http://www.gsdma.org/hazard/eq/200_year.jpg |title=Gujarat Earthquake Hazard Risk Zone |accessdate=23 August 2006 |publisher=Gujarat State Disaster Management Authority |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929061637/http://www.gsdma.org/hazard/eq/200_year.jpg |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref>\n{{wide image|Baroda Lvp.JPG|1000x300px|align-cap=center|Panorama of Laxmi Vilas Palace}}\n\n==Climate==\n\nDespite the roughly 800&nbsp;mm of precipitation that the city receives annually, Vadodara features a [[semi-arid climate]] (BSh) under [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen's Climate classification]] due to the area's high [[potential evapotranspiration]]. There are three main seasons: Summer, [[Monsoon]] and Winter. Aside from the monsoon season, the climate is dry. The weather is hot during March to July, when the average maximum is {{convert|45|\u00b0C}}, and the average minimum is {{convert|23|C}}. From November to February, the average maximum temperature is {{convert|30|\u00b0C}}, the average minimum is {{convert|15|\u00b0C}}, and the climate is extremely dry. Cold northerly winds are responsible for a mild chilly days in January. The southwest monsoon brings a humid climate from mid-June to mid-September. The average rainfall is {{convert|93|cm|in|abbr=on}}, but infrequent heavy torrential rains cause the river to flood<ref name=\"Weatherbase\">{{cite web|title=Baroda, India (2~35 kilometers)|url=http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=74724&units=metric|accessdate=6 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211144022/http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=74724&units=metric|archive-date=11 December 2013|url-status=live}}{{better source|date=December 2013}}</ref> like the [[2005 Gujarat Flood|2005 Gujarat flood]] or the [[2008 Indian floods]] which were catastrophic.<ref name=\"floods\">{{cite web | url=http://www.iahv.org/in-en/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Gujarat-Floods-2005-Report.pdf | title=Gujarat Floods 2005: Project Report | publisher=International Association for Human Values and the Art of Living | date=2005 | accessdate=2 November 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112001510/http://www.iahv.org/in-en/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/Gujarat-Floods-2005-Report.pdf | archive-date=12 January 2016 | url-status=live | df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe highest recorded temperature was {{convert|46.7|C}} on 11 May 1960 crossed with {{convert|48.0|C}} on 19 May 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.accuweather.com/en/in/vadodara/202439/may-weather/202439|title=Vadodara May Weather 2016 \u2013 AccuWeather Forecast for Gujarat India|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160930070904/http://www.accuweather.com/en/in/vadodara/202439/may-weather/202439|archive-date=30 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> while the lowest recorded temperature was {{convert|-1.1|C}} on 15 January 1935.<ref name=\"IMD\">{{cite web |url=http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf |title=Ever Recorded Maximum/Minimum Temperature up to 2010 |publisher=India Meteorological Department |accessdate=16 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140316064314/http://www.imdpune.gov.in/Temp_Extremes/histext2010.pdf |archive-date=16 March 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n{{weather box|width=auto\n|location = Vadodara\n|metric first = yes\n|single line = yes\n|Jan record high C = 36.2\n|Feb record high C = 41.7\n|Mar record high C = 44.4\n|Apr record high C = 45.9\n|May record high C = 48.0\n|Jun record high C = 45.6\n|Jul record high C = 40.6\n|Aug record high C = 37.9\n|Sep record high C = 41.1\n|Oct record high C = 42.1\n|Nov record high C = 39.6\n|Dec record high C = 36.8\n\n|Jan high C = 29.5\n|Feb high C = 31.9\n|Mar high C = 36.2\n|Apr high C = 39.2\n|May high C = 40.1\n|Jun high C = 36.8\n|Jul high C = 32.5\n|Aug high C = 31.4\n|Sep high C = 33.0\n|Oct high C = 35.5\n|Nov high C = 33.4\n|Dec high C = 30.7\n\n|Jan low C = 12.5\n|Feb low C = 14.2\n|Mar low C = 18.4\n|Apr low C = 23.0\n|May low C = 26.6\n|Jun low C = 27.0\n|Jul low C = 25.8\n|Aug low C = 25.0\n|Sep low C = 24.5\n|Oct low C = 21.4\n|Nov low C = 16.9\n|Dec low C = 13.7\n\n|Jan record low C = \u22121.1\n|Feb record low C =  1.7\n|Mar record low C =  6.7\n|Apr record low C = 11.7\n|May record low C = 18.9\n|Jun record low C = 20.2\n|Jul record low C = 21.1\n|Aug record low C = 22.2\n|Sep record low C = 18.9\n|Oct record low C = 11.7\n|Nov record low C =  7.2\n|Dec record low C =  3.3\n\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation mm=   2.2\n|Feb precipitation mm=   0.7\n|Mar precipitation mm=   0.7\n|Apr precipitation mm=   1.4\n|May precipitation mm=   6.1\n|Jun precipitation mm= 118.9\n|Jul precipitation mm= 274.6\n|Aug precipitation mm= 242.4\n|Sep precipitation mm= 124.2\n|Oct precipitation mm=  26.4\n|Nov precipitation mm=   1.3\n|Dec precipitation mm=   3.7\n\n|Jan humidity=45\n|Feb humidity=43\n|Mar humidity=35\n|Apr humidity=33\n|May humidity=49\n|Jun humidity=67\n|Jul humidity=80\n|Aug humidity=75\n|Sep humidity=73\n|Oct humidity=62\n|Nov humidity=58\n|Dec humidity=54\n|year humidity=56\n\n|Jan rain days=0\n|Feb rain days=0\n|Mar rain days=0\n|Apr rain days=0\n|May rain days=0\n|Jun rain days=9\n|Jul rain days=14\n|Aug rain days=11\n|Sep rain days=7\n|Oct rain days=3\n|Nov rain days=1\n|Dec rain days=0\n|year rain days=49\n\n|source 1 = India Meteorological Department (1952\u20132000)<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Climate of Vadodara\n |url          = http://www.imd.gov.in/doc/climateimp.pdf\n |publisher    = India meteorological department\n |accessdate   = 31 May 2014\n |archiveurl   = https://web.archive.org/web/20150413020426/http://www.imd.gov.in/doc/climateimp.pdf\n |url-status      = dead\n |archive-date = 13 April 2015\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n|source 2 = [http://www.weatherbase.com/weather/weather.php3?s=595703&cityname=Vadodara%2C+Gujarat%2C+India Weatherbase] (Avg. rainy days)\n}}\n\n==Economy==\nIn Vadodara various large-scale industries such as Indian Oil Corporation(IOCL), Gujarat State Fertilizers & Chemicals (GSFC), [[Indian Petrochemicals Corporation Limited]] (IPCL, now owned by [[Reliance Industries Limited]]) and Gujarat Alkalies and Chemicals Limited (GACL) have come up in the vicinity of [[Gujarat Refinery]] and all of them are dependent on it for their fuel and feedstock. Other large-scale public sector units are Heavy Water Project, Gujarat Industries Power Company Limited (GIPCL), [[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation]] (ONGC) & Gas Authority of India Limited ([[GAIL]]). In addition to these public sector enterprises, a number of other large-scale enterprises have come up in the private sector such as Avalance Global Solutions, [[Bombardier Transportation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bombardier.com/en/corporate/about-us/worldwide-presence/india?docID=0901260d8001725d# |title=Corporate > About Us > Worldwide Presence > India |publisher=Bombardier.com |accessdate=26 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601125717/http://www.bombardier.com/en/corporate/about-us/worldwide-presence/india?docID=0901260d8001725d |archive-date=1 June 2012 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>[http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/wealth/credit-cards/news/mastercard-launches-technology-hub-in-india-with-facilities-in-pune-and-vadodara/articleshow/46127416.cms MasterCard launches technology hub in India with facilities in Pune and Vadodara \u2013 The Economic Times] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207120802/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/wealth/credit-cards/news/mastercard-launches-technology-hub-in-india-with-facilities-in-pune-and-vadodara/articleshow/46127416.cms |date=7 February 2015 }}. Economictimes.indiatimes.com (5 February 2015). Retrieved on 10 October 2015.</ref>\n\nLocated in Vadodara are over 35% India's power transmission and distribution equipment manufacturers and an estimated 800 ancillaries supporting the big players in Power Sector equipment manufacturing and engineering industry.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/Switch-conference-at-Vadodara-in-October/articleshow/53486393.cms Switch conference at Vadodara in October \u2013 The Times of India] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160809024143/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/Switch-conference-at-Vadodara-in-October/articleshow/53486393.cms |date=9 August 2016 }}. timesofindia.indiatimes.com (1 August 2016).</ref>\n\nVadodara is also home to the [[Vadodara Stock Exchange]] (VSE).\n\n==Civic administration==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellspacing=\"1\"  style=\"float:right; width:260px; margin:10px; background:#f4f5f6; border:#c6c7c8 solid; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" bgcolour=\"#C2D6E5\" style=\"text-align:left;\"| '''Vadodara City Officials'''\n|-\n| style=\"width:50%;\"| '''Mayor'''\n| Dr. Jigeeshaben Jatinbhai Sheth<ref name=\"mayor_name\">{{Cite web |url=https://vmc.gov.in/ViewContacts.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920123041/https://vmc.gov.in/ViewContacts.aspx |archive-date=20 September 2018 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n|-\n| '''Municipal Commissioner'''\n| Shri Nalin Upadhyay\n|-\n| '''Police Commissioner'''\n| Anupamsinh Gehlot IPS\n|}\n[[File:Baroda KM.jpg|thumb|right|[[Khanderao Market, Vadodara|Khanderao Market]] \u2013 [[Vadodara Mahanagar Seva Sadan]] Building]]\n\nThe two main institutions involved in planning and development in Vadodara are VMSS and the VUDA. The jurisdiction of both these agencies is demarcated clearly not only physically but also functionally. The governing acts for both the institutions differ. The principal responsibility of VUDA is to ensure a holistic development of the Vadodara agglomeration covering an area of {{convert|714.56|km2|abbr=on}},<ref name=zone>{{cite web|publisher=Vadodara Municipal Corporation |title=Institutional Setup in Vadodara |url=http://www.vadodaracity.com/cdp_pdf/Link%206.pdf |accessdate=29 July 2007 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929050939/http://www.vadodaracity.com/cdp_pdf/Link%206.pdf |archivedate=29 September 2007 }}</ref> whereas VMSS is involved in the development of area of {{convert|235|km2|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"zone\"/>\n\nThree [[Local Governance in India|corporators]] are elected from each ward, who in turn elect a mayor. Executive powers are vested in the municipal commissioner, who is an [[Indian Administrative Service|IAS]] officer appointed by the Gujarat state government. The mayor is responsible for the day-to-day running of the city services, municipal school board, the city bus service, the municipal hospital and the city library. The Vadodara City Police is headed by a [[Police Commissioner]], an [[Indian Police Service|IPS]] officer.\n\nThe City elects 1<ref name=\"LSMLA\">{{cite web |publisher=Gujarat Assembly |title=List of Lok Sabha Constituencies from Gujarat |url=http://www.gujaratassembly.gov.in/loksabhamember.htm |accessdate=1 October 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050302161941/http://www.gujaratassembly.gov.in/loksabhamember.htm |archive-date=2 March 2005 |url-status=live  }}</ref> member to the [[Lok Sabha]] (parliament) and 5<ref name=\"MLA\">{{cite web|publisher=Gujarat Assembly|title=List of MLAs from Vadodara District|url=http://www.gujaratassembly.gov.in/epvadodara.htm|accessdate=30 June 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924024211/http://www.gujaratassembly.gov.in/epvadodara.htm|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> to the Gujarat [[Vidhan Sabha]](Assembly) All of the 5 assembly seats of Vadodara were won by the [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] during the legislative elections in 2002. In the 2006 VMSS elections, the BJP won 74<ref name=hindu>{{cite news |publisher=The Hindu Daily |title=Sweeping victory for BJP in Gujarat civic polls |url=http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/14/stories/2005121406311300.htm |accessdate=9 July 2007 |location=Chennai, India |date=14 December 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001064306/http://www.hindu.com/2005/12/14/stories/2005121406311300.htm |archive-date=1 October 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref> seats, 6 seats went to the Congress.\n\n*Election Wards: 38<ref name=\"zone\"/>\n*Seats (Corporators): 114<ref name=\"zone\"/>\n*Population per ward: 31,122\n*Seats reserved for women: 38\n*Total voters (as on 1 January 2019): 1,638,321\n\nThe Vadodara City Police are responsible for law enforcement and public safety in Vadodara, India. They are a subdivision of the state police force of [[Gujarat]] and are headed by a commissioner. The Vadodara police force is responsible for the protection and safety of Vadodara citizens. Shri Anupam Singh Gahlaut is the current Commissioner of Vadodara City Police.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cpvadodara.gujarat.gov.in/cpvadodara/default.aspx|title=Vadodara City Police \u2013 Details|website=cpvadodara.gujarat.gov.in|access-date=22 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190322091952/https://www.cpvadodara.gujarat.gov.in/cpvadodara/default.aspx|archive-date=22 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe city is on the major rail and road arteries joining [[Mumbai]] with [[Delhi]] and Mumbai with [[Ahmedabad]].\n\n===Air===\n[[Vadodara Airport]] ([[IATA]]: '''BDQ''') is located north-east of the city. Vadodara has flight connections with Mumbai, New Delhi, Hyderabad and Bangalore. Air India and IndiGo are currently operating their services from the airport.A new integrated international terminal has been constructed at the Vadodara airport and was inaugurated in October 2016. Vadodara is the first Green Airport in Gujarat and Second Green Airport in India after Kochi.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dnasyndication.com/showarticlerss.aspx?nid=muaqdWy43dPulsTSLyQpFxAFCY2RaiKae8NcPA21HKE4KNcM=|title=Vadodara\u2019s new airport makes place in Limca Record|publisher=Dnasyndication.com|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170510073233/http://dnasyndication.com/showarticlerss.aspx?nid=muaqdWy43dPulsTSLyQpFxAFCY2RaiKae8NcPA21HKE4KNcM=|archive-date=10 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/pm-modi-inaugurates-new-international-terminal-at-vadodara-airport-116102200655_1.html|title=Vadodara gets India's second green airport after Kochi|first=Vimukt|last=Dave|date=22 October 2016|accessdate=26 November 2016|via=Business Standard|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161023201842/http://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/pm-modi-inaugurates-new-international-terminal-at-vadodara-airport-116102200655_1.html|archive-date=23 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/PM-Narendra-Modi-inaugurates-Vadodara-International-Airport/articleshow/54998435.cms|title=PM Narendra Modi inaugurates Vadodara International Airport \u2013 Times of India \u25ba|website=The Times of India|access-date=10 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518060953/http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/pm-narendra-modi-inaugurates-vadodara-international-airport/articleshow/54998435.cms|archive-date=18 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schwartzarch.com/projects/vadodara_airport.html|title=Vadodara Airport -[FSA]-|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160421041259/http://www.schwartzarch.com/projects/vadodara_airport.html|archive-date=21 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gensler.com/projects/vadodara-international-airport|title=Vadodara International Airport \u2013 Projects \u2013 Gensler|accessdate=26 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161114004035/http://www.gensler.com/projects/vadodara-international-airport|archive-date=14 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Railway===\n[[File:Vadrail.jpg|thumb|Vadodara Junction Railway Station]]\n\nVadodara was part of the historic [[Bombay, Baroda and Central India Railway]] (BBCI), which arrived in the city in January 1861.<ref name=BBCI>{{cite news |publisher=Times of India|title=150th year of Railway in Vadodara|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/150th-year-of-rlys-in-city-to-be-celebrated-on-Jan-9/articleshow/5371170.cms |accessdate=24 December 2009|first1=Sachin|last1=Sharma|date=23 December 2009}}</ref> On 5 November 1951 the BBCI Railway was merged with the [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], [[Rajputana]] and [[Jaipur]] railways to create the [[Western Railway (India)|Western Railway]]. [[Vadodara Railway Station]] now belongs to the Western Railway zone of [[Indian Railways]] and is a major junction on the Western Railway Main Line.\n\nThe under-construction [[Mumbai\u2013Ahmedabad high-speed rail corridor]], India's first [[High-speed rail]] line will have a stop at the existing [[Vadodara Junction railway station]]. The station is planned for renovation to accommodate the new line<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.financialexpress.com/infrastructure/railways/mumbai-ahmedabad-bullet-train-project-construction-work-on-swanky-vadodara-railway-station-to-begin-soon/1413870/|title=Mumbai-Ahmedabad bullet train project: Construction work on swanky Vadodara railway station to begin soon|date=2018-12-14|website=The Financial Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-02}}</ref>.  \n\n==Demographics==\nAccording to the 2011 India census, Vadodara metropolitan area had a population of {{formatnum:1,822,221}}.  In Vadodara, 9% of the population is under 6 years of age.<ref name=\"Vadodara City Census 2011 data\">[http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/338-vadodara.html Vadodara City Census 2011 data] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522144222/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/338-vadodara.html |date=22 May 2012 }}. Census2011.co.in. Retrieved on 10 October 2015.</ref> [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Urdu]], [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Hindi]] and English are the languages spoken in the city. Males constitute 52% of the population and females 48%.\n{{IndiaCensusPop|state=\n|title= Population Growth of Vadodara\n|1820= 100000\n|1865= 140000\n|1881= 101800\n|1891= 116400\n|1901= 103800\n|1911= 99300\n|1921= 94700\n|1931= 112900\n|1941= 153300\n|1951= 211400\n|1961= 295100\n|1968= 400700\n|1971= 467000\n|1981= 744000\n|1991= 1126800\n|2001= 1491045\n|2011= 1822221\n|footnote= source:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.populstat.info/Asia/indiat.htm|title=Historical Census of India|access-date=23 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217053707/http://www.populstat.info/Asia/indiat.htm|archive-date=17 February 2013|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"censusindia1\">{{cite web|url=http://citypopulation.de/world/Agglomerations.html|title=Census of World|access-date=23 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160402222958/http://citypopulation.de/world/Agglomerations.html|archive-date=2 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n}}\n{{bar box\n|title=Religions in Vadodara city (2011)<ref name=\"Vadodara City Census 2011 data\"/>\n|titlebar=#Fcd116\n|float=left\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Hinduism]]|orange|85.39}}\n{{bar percent|[[Islam]]|green|11.40}}\n{{bar percent|[[Jainism]]|blue|1.32}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christianity]]|pink|1.22}}\n{{bar percent|[[Sikhism]]|yellow|0.45}}\n{{bar percent|Others|black|0.22}}\n|caption=Distribution of religions\n}}\n\n===Religions and festivals===\n[[File:UWoB2011.jpg|thumb|left|United Way of Baroda Garba Festival in 2011]]\n[[File:BuddhaStatue JubileeBaug Baroda ca1931.jpg|thumb|Buddha Statute erected 1930 in the '#Jubilee Park'' (Jubilee Baug).]]\n\nThe most followed religion in the city is Hinduism, practiced by 85% of the population. The second most followed religion is Islam, followed by 11% of the population. All other religious groups make up the remaining 4% of the population.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/338-vadodara.html|title=Vadodara City Population Census 2011\u20132019 \u2013 Gujarat|website=www.census2011.co.in|access-date=12 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522144222/http://www.census2011.co.in/census/city/338-vadodara.html|archive-date=22 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Sports==\nVadodara has a professional cricket team, the [[Baroda cricket team]], as well as the oldest cricket ground in Asia, called [[Moti Bagh Stadium|Moti Baug]].<ref name=Moti>{{cite web|publisher=Cricinfo|title=Ground Profile|url=http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/ground/58516.html#Profile|accessdate=17 November 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081228202856/http://content-www.cricinfo.com/ci/content/ground/58516.html#Profile|archive-date=28 December 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> The team has won the [[Ranji Trophy]] six times. [[IPCL Sports Complex Ground|Reliance Stadium]], a private cricket ground owned by [[Reliance Industries]], hosts [[One Day International|ODI]]s. Some of the notable cricketer's from Baroda are [[Kiran More]], [[Nayan Mongia]], [[Atul Bedade]], [[Irfan Pathan]], [[Yusuf Pathan]], [[Hardik Pandya]],  [[Krunal Pandya]], [[Deepak Hooda]].\n\n==Media==\nThe city has five local [[frequency modulation|FM]] stations: [[Radio City (India radio station)|Radio City]] (91.1&nbsp;[[hertz|MHz]]), [[Radio Mirchi]] (98.3&nbsp;[[hertz|MHz]]),  [[Red FM 93.5|Red FM]] (93.5&nbsp;[[hertz|MHz]]), [[BIG FM 92.7|Big FM]] (92.7&nbsp;[[hertz|MHz]]),  and [[All India Radio]], [[Vividh Bharti]] (93.9&nbsp;[[hertz|MHz]])(Aakashwani). [[Radio City (India radio station)|Radio City]] (91.1&nbsp;[[hertz|MHz]]) is known all over Vadodara for its Rag Rag Ma Vadodara City profile. All India Radio is broadcast on the [[amplitude modulation|AM]] band.<ref name=Radio>{{cite web |publisher=Asiawaves |title=Radio Stations in Gujarat, India |url=http://www.asiawaves.net/india/gujarat-radio.htm |accessdate=14 June 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527085052/http://www.asiawaves.net/india/gujarat-radio.htm |archive-date=27 May 2007 |url-status=live  }}</ref> [[Satellite radio]] was launched in nearby city of Ahmedabad by [[WorldSpace]] in 2005.<ref name=Worldspace>{{cite web |publisher=Worldspace Satellite Radio |title=WorldSpace Satellite Radio Lights Up Ahmedabad |url=http://www.worldspace.com/press/11_03_2005.html |date=3 November 2005 |accessdate=30 July 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061112064236/http://www.worldspace.com/press/11_03_2005.html |archive-date=12 November 2006 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Vadodara News Magazine(VNM) is a local news TV channel that covers events in the city.\n\n== Temple ==\n\nA non-sectarian Temple<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.trimandir.org/list-of-trimandirs/vadodara-trimandir/|title=About Temple|website=www.trimandir.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> inspired by Akram Vignani, Dada Bhagwan located near Babaria college, NH 48.\n\n== Education ==\nThe city houses many Schools and Colleges. Higher Education Institutions across various disciplines attract international students mainly from the African countries such as Ethiopia, Zimbabwe, Malawi, South Africa, and Kenya.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/education/gujarat-more-foreign-students-opt-for-msu-5857416/|title=Gujarat: More foreign students opt for MS University of Baroda|date=2019-07-28|website=The Indian Express|language=en-IN|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n\n=== Universities ===\n\n* [[Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda|The Maharaja Sayajirao University of Baroda]]\n* [[Parul University]]\n* [[Navrachana University|Navrachna University]]\n* [[GSFC University]]\n* [[National Rail and Transportation Institute]] (Railway University) \n* ITM Vocational University\n* Sumandeep Vidyapeeth\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Desai\n|first = Anjali\n|title=India Guide, Gujarat \u2013 Visitor's Guide\n|publisher=India Guide Publications\n|isbn = 0-9789517-0-0\n }}\n* {{cite book\n|last = F. A. H Elliot\n|first =\n|title=The rulers of Baroda\n|publisher=Baroda State Press 1934\n|ASIN = B0006C35QS}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Gense\n|first = James\n|title=The Gaikwads of Baroda\n|url = https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.283204\n|publisher=D.B. Taraporevala Sons & Co 1942\n|ASIN = B0007K1PL6}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Kothekara\n|first = Santa\n|title=The Gaikwads of Baroda and the East India Company, 1770\u20131820\n|publisher=Nagpur University\n|ASIN = B0006D2LAI}}\n* {{cite book\n|last = Gaekwad\n|first = Fatesinghrao\n|title=Sayajirao of Baroda: The Prince and the Man\n|publisher=[[Popular Prakashan]]\n|isbn = 978-0-86132-214-5\n }}\n* {{cite book\n|last